Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Put your @brown basmati rice{1} in a #sieve{} (if you have one) and run cold water through it for at least ~{30%seconds}. Once the water is boiling, add the rice to the pot and cook on a rapid boil for ~{25%minutes}. When the rice is cooked, take off the heat, drain, cover with a #tea towel{} and leave until everything else is ready.

> Tip: If your rice dries out before it's cooked, simply add some more water to the pot.

While the rice is cooking start making your chana masala! Peel and chop your @onion{1}(peeled and roughly chopped) into roughly 1cm pieces. Peel and finely chop your @garlic clove{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Peel your @ginger{1}(peeled and finely chopped) (you can do this with the back of a spoon!) and finely chop. Finely chop half your @green chilli{1/2}(finely chopped).

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a #saucepan{} on medium heat and add the onion, garlic, ginger and chilli (the amount you add depends on how spicy you like things!). Cook for ~{5%mins}, stirring occasionally, until the onion is soft, then add your @South Indian spice mix{5.5%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute}, stirring a few times before adding your @tomato puree{1} and cooking for a further ~{1%minute}.

Add the @chopped tomatoes{1} to the pan, refill the tin a quarter with water and add this to the pan as well, stir. Drain the @chickpeas{1%tin} and add them to the pan too. Add @salt{1/4%tsp}, a good grind of @ground black pepper{1%grind} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} (if you have any!), stir together and cook uncovered for ~{10%mins} on medium heat, until everything has reduced slightly and the chickpeas are soft.

While the chana masala is cooking, make your raita! Chop a quarter of your @cucumber{1/4}(chopped into roughly 1/2cm cubes) and roughly chop your @coriander{3}(roughly chopped). Mix your cucumber and half your coriander together with your @Greek style natural yoghurt{1}. Squeeze in @lemon{1/2}(juiced) 1 tsp of lemon juice, add @salt{pinch} and give it a good stir to combine.

When the chana masala has reduced slightly and is lovely and thick, add your @baby spinach{3}, put your lid on and let the spinach wilt for ~{2%mins}. Then take the lid off and stir the spinach through. Serve the chana masala on a bed of lovely brown rice, with the raita on the side and some coriander sprinkled over the top. Enjoy!